    <note>Zhou(1) Nan [7196] Wei(4) Jimin's [7387] son-in-law, whose daughter, 衛琮, is not listed as a wife in Ye Shi's funerary inscription for Nan, and who probably died early without bearing any children. Wei(4) Pu's [4000] father-in-law. Nan is related to Zhou(1) Hu [3245], whose 7th generation ancestor, Jingshu [3241], was Jiazheng's [480] father. Hu's family moved from Taizhou, Hailing xian to Suzhou, Changshu xian during the Jin invasions in 1126-27. Hu's father, Zongli [16345], is identified as a grandfather (xianzu) by Zhou(1) Nan in his funerary inscription for Zongli's wife, born He(2). While clearly not Nan's grandfather, he must be a lineage granduncle. Nan was a Wuxian resident and it is not clear when the two branches of the lineage segemented or when Nan's ancestors moved to Suzhou. I am assuming that both branches trace back to Jingshu, who moved to Taizhou from Sichuan at the beginning of the dynasty. Zhou Nan, WJ, 5.16b; Liu Zai, WJ, 32.19b; Suzhou FZ, 98.11a; Ye Shi, WJ, 20.381-384. CBD, 2, 1442.</note>
